<section xml:id="sec-hire-purchase-ii" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Hire Purchase II</title>
    <!--  -->
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.4 Commercial Arithmetic
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Determine the cost of goods in purchase
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <p>
                By the end of this lesson, the learner should be able to break down a compound credit purchase into its constituent parts (deposit, principal balance, and flat or compound interest charges) and analyze how varying repayment timelines impact the total carrying charge.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Core Competencies Developed:</alert>
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Critical Thinking and Problem Solving:</term> Developed as learners evaluate real-world case studies to weigh the immediate utility of an asset against its long-term cost of credit.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <term>Financial Literacy &amp; Citizenship:</term> Enhanced as learners investigate credit options within their local community and practice making prudent consumer decisions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Values Infused:</alert> Responsibility and integrity in personal financial management, and cooperation during collaborative group computations.
            </p>
        </axiom>
    </objectives>

    <activity>
        <statement>

            <p>
                <term>Work in Groups</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                In real life, individuals and institutions make financial decisions that involve borrowing or deferred payment. These decisions are influenced by interest, repayment time, and affordability.
            </p>

            <p>
                In this activity, you will investigate how hire purchase arrangements affect the total cost of goods and how financial institutions structure repayment systems to generate interest.
            </p>

            <p>
                Identify and discuss situations in your community where people purchase goods on credit and end up paying more than the cash price. Record your findings in the table below.
            </p>

            <tabular top="medium" bottom="medium" right="medium" left="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Item Bought on Hire Purchase</cell>
                    <cell>Observed Financial Impact</cell>
                    <cell>Reason for Extra Cost</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Motorbike</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Television</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Smartphone</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                    <cell>?</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>

            <p>
                <alert>Group Study</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                A motorbike is sold at a cash price of Ksh <m>120,000</m>. A buyer pays a deposit of <m>25\%</m> and the balance is repaid under a hire purchase agreement where simple interest is charged at <m>12\%</m> per annum for <m>2</m> years.
            </p>

            <p>
                Solve in groups and present your findings to the class. Consider the following questions as you work through the problem.
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>Determine the deposit and outstanding balance.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Compute the total interest charged on the balance.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Determine the total hire purchase price.</p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>Compare the hire purchase price with the cash price and compute the percentage increase.</p>
                    </li>
                    
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p>
                Suppose the repayment period is extended from 2 years to 3 years while keeping all other conditions constant.
            </p>

            <p>
                Discuss:
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>How does the total cost change?</li>
                    <li>What happens to the interest charged?</li>
                    <li>Is the buyer financially better or worse off? Justify mathematically and logically.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p>
                <alert>Decision-Making Task:</alert>
            </p>

            <p>
                Compare the hire purchase option with a cash purchase scenario where the buyer must save for 2 years before purchasing the same motorbike. Discuss:
            </p>

            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>Opportunity cost of waiting versus buying immediately</li>
                    <li>Financial burden of instalments versus saving discipline</li>
                    <li>Which option is economically rational and why</li>
                </ol>
            </p>

        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        10 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To formalize how interest models (flat rate simple interest versus compound reducing balance interest) are mathematically layered onto outstanding credit balances.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Walk the class through the case study of the Ksh 120,000 motorbike. Point out that after paying a 25% deposit (Ksh 30,000), the interest is <em>not</em> calculated on the original price. It is calculated strictly on the outstanding balance of Ksh 90,000, revealing how merchants use simple interest (<m>I = \frac{PRT}{100}</m>) to determine carrying costs.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Critical Thinking Debriefing:</alert> Lead a discussion based on the Higher Order Thinking Task. Show that extending a repayment period reduces individual monthly payments but increases total interest accrued over time. This helps learners understand that minimizing monthly payments often results in a higher total cost of ownership.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Socio-Economic Competency:</alert> Guide learners through the Decision-Making Task. Emphasize that choosing between hire purchase and delayed cash purchase is a trade-off between immediate utility (gaining access to a motorbike for an enterprise right away) and absolute financial efficiency (avoiding interest fees).
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <insight>
        <p>
            Hire purchase is a credit-based purchasing system where a buyer acquires goods immediately by paying a deposit and settles the remaining balance over time with interest.
        </p>

        <p>
            In advanced financial analysis, hire purchase is not only about instalments but about the <term>cost of credit</term>, which depends on time, interest rate, and outstanding balance.
        </p>

        <p>
            The structure of hire purchase can be summarised as:
        </p>

        <p>
            <md>
                <mrow> \text{Deposit} = \amp \; \text{Initial percentage of cash price} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Balance} = \amp \; \text{Cash price} - \text{Deposit} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Interest} = \amp \; \frac{PRT}{100} \; \text{(or appropriate model)} </mrow>
                <mrow> \text{Hire Purchase Price} = \amp \; \text{Deposit} + \text{Balance + Interest} </mrow>
            </md>
        </p>

        <p>
            A key financial principle is that:
        </p>

        <p>
            <em>
                As the repayment period increases, the total cost of ownership increases due to accumulation of interest.
            </em>
        </p>

        <p>
            Therefore, rational financial decision-making requires comparing cash price, hire purchase price, and time-based cost implications before committing to a purchase.
        </p>
    </insight>

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <title>Calculating Hire Purchase Price with Simple Interest on Balance</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                An agricultural water pump is sold at a cash price of Ksh <m>80,000</m>. A farmer opts for a hire purchase plan by paying a <m>30\%</m> deposit, with the remaining balance attracting simple interest at a flat rate of <m>10\%</m> per annum over a repayment period of <m>1.5</m> years. Determine the total hire purchase price and the monthly installment amount.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 1: Calculate the deposit and outstanding balance.</alert>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Deposit (D)} \amp = \; \frac{30}{100} \times 80,000 = \text{Ksh } 24,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Principal Balance (P)} \amp = \; 80,000 - 24,000 = \text{Ksh } 56,000 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 2: Compute the simple interest charged on the balance.</alert>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Interest (I)} \amp = \; \frac{P \times R \times T}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; \frac{56,000 \times 10 \times 1.5}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 560 \times 15 = \text{Ksh } 8,400 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Step 3: Determine the total hire purchase price and installments.</alert>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Total Accrued Balance} \amp = \; \text{Balance} + \text{Interest} = 56,000 + 8,400 = \text{Ksh } 64,400 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Hire Purchase Price (H)} \amp = \; \text{Deposit} + \text{Total Accrued Balance} </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 24,000 + 64,400 = \text{Ksh } 88,400 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The total number of months is <m>1.5 \times 12 = 18</m> months. Therefore, the monthly installment amount is:
                <m>\text{Monthly Installment} = \frac{64,400}{18} \approx \text{Ksh } 3,577.78</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A sofa set has a cash price of Ksh <m>50,000</m>. To buy it on hire purchase, a customer pays a deposit of Ksh <m>10,000</m> and <m>12</m> monthly installments of Ksh <m>4,000</m>. Calculate the annual flat rate of interest charged on the balance.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance} \amp = \;50,000 - 10,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 40,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total Paid in Installments} \amp = \; 12 \times 4,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 48,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Interest Paid} \amp = \; 48,000 - 40,000 = \text{Ksh}\; 8,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> I \amp = \; \frac{P \times R \times T}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> 8,000 \amp = \; \frac{40,000 \times R \times 1}{100} </mrow>
                    <mrow> 8,000 \amp = 400 R </mrow>
                    <mrow> R \amp = \; 20 \% \; \text{Per annum} </mrow>
                </md>
                
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A motorcycle costs Ksh <m>100,000</m> cash. A buyer pays a <m>20\%</m> deposit. The remaining balance is subject to compound interest at a rate of <m>15\%</m> p.a. for <m>2 </m> years. Calculate the total Hire Purchase Price.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Deposit:} \amp \; \frac{20}{100}\times 100,000 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 20,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance:} \amp \; 100,000 - 20,000 = \text{Ksh}\; 80,000</mrow>
                    <mrow> A \amp = \; P(1 + R)^T </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 80,000(1 + \frac{15}{100})^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \amp = \; 80,000 (1.15)^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> =  \amp \; 105,800 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>\text{Total hire purchase} = 20,000 + 105,800 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 125,800 </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A laptop costs Ksh <m>40,000</m> cash. The hire purchase plan requires a Ksh <m>10,000</m> deposit and a flat interest rate of <m>10\%</m> p.a. If the monthly installment is Ksh <m>2,750</m>, how many months will it take to clear the debt?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Balance:} \amp \; 40,000 - 10,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 30,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Interest for 1 Year:} \; \amp \frac{10}{100} \times 30,000 = \;\text{Ksh} \; 3,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Total instalments:} \amp \; 30,000 + 3,000 = \;\text{Ksh}\; 33,000 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Number of months:} \amp \; \frac{33,000}{2,750} = 12 \;\text{months} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- If STACK questions are included, uncomment this: -->

    <!-- <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/checkpoint.ptx" /> -->

    <!-- Add STACK exercises if made -->

    <!-- Add static exercises -->
     <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A bicycle costs Ksh <m>12,000</m> cash. The HPP is Ksh <m>15,000</m> with a Ksh <m>3,000</m> deposit. If the installments are spread over <m>1</m> year, find the annual flat rate of interest.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>33.33\%</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A small business buys a delivery van worth Ksh <m>1,200,000</m>. They pay a <m>40\%</m> deposit. The dealer charges <m>12\%</m> p.a. compound interest on the reducing balance for a period of <m>2</m> years. The total remaining amount is then cleared in <m>24</m> equal monthly installments. Find the value of one installment.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>\text{Ksh}\; 37,632</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    An oven's cash price is Ksh <m>20,000</m>. Hire purchase requires a Ksh <m>4,000</m> deposit and <m>12</m> installments of Ksh <m>1,600</m>. Find the total interest and the flat interest rate.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>3,200 \;\text{Interest}, \text{Rate} \;20\%</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A student bought a laptop on hire purchase. He paid a deposit of Ksh <m>12,000</m>, which was <m>15\%</m> of the total Hire purchase price. He then paid the remaining amount in <m>12</m> monthly installments. If the dealer charged a flat interest of Ksh <m>5,000</m> on the cash price balance, what was the original Cash Price of the laptop?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Ksh <m>75,000</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
     </exercises>

    

    <!-- [LP] Add information on how to differentiate  -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation Matrix for Advanced Hire Purchase</title>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" bottom="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>Struggling Learners (Support)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Provide highly guided instruction using a step-by-step breakdown of hire purchase concepts (deposit, balance, total cost). Use simplified numbers and familiar real-life items such as smartphones or bicycles to build baseline understanding.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The teacher models each calculation sequence before learners attempt similar practice problems. Provide structured worksheets with visual hints and partially completed execution lines, and allow strategic use of calculators and peer support to manage cognitive load.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell><alert>On-Level Learners (Core)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Learners independently extract problem variables to apply formulas such as <m>H = D + xn</m> alongside base interest equations to solve real-world hire purchase scenarios.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            They work through structured group activities involving the calculation of complete carrying charges, percentage increases, and spot-cash alternatives. Practice translating complex multi-sentence word problems into clean mathematical expressions, engaging in class discussions to justify mathematical choices.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>

                <row>
                    <cell><alert>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</alert></cell>
                    <cell>
                        <p>
                            Extend problems to include compound interest accumulation on reducing credit balances and complex multi-tier financial options. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Task learners with analyzing and contrasting diverse credit options (e.g., hire purchase plans versus commercial bank loans versus disciplined personal savings timelines). They investigate structural dependencies mathematically to justify the most economical choice, and author their own contextual application problems for peer review.
                        </p>
                    </cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
